The unique design of the lubricating oil high pressure relief valve, 552 kPa (80 psi) located in the front cover ( Figure i.10
) and the oil pressure regulating valve [345 kPa (50 psi)], located by the rear oil cooler header ( Figure i.11
), extends the life of the engine because it controls the volume and pressure of oil supplied to the engine. The volume of oil supplied by the pump is always in excess of what is needed to lubricate the engine. The oil high pressure relief valve is located in the front cover and is used to protect the oil cooler and oil filter from extremely high pressures encountered during cold starts in cold weather. If oil pressure exceeds 552 kPa (80 psi) on the valve face, it moves the valve inward allowing oil to travel through the valve and back to the oil pan, thus relieving pressure in the lubrication system.
